<paragraph id="ABAE9D38310ACFFB897A2D05BC8F00EB" pageId="0" pageNumber="8176">Notes</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4984C9BB0FF39B4E3C28AA1B47D2972F" pageId="0" pageNumber="8176">
<taxonomicName id="ED7AD054299919F88B27325415930FAC" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Tamaricaceae" genus="Tamarix" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Tamarix chinensis" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="0" pageNumber="8176" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="chinensis">Tamarix chinensis</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="D5780F029A391237019142B299637899" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Tamaricaceae" genus="Tamarix" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Tamarix ramosissima" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="0" pageNumber="8176" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ramosissima">Tamarix ramosissima</taxonomicName>
are both highly invasive within the western U.S.A. (Gaskin and Kazmer 2009). 
<taxonomicName id="1EDB4C8B9A6DFBED37AF8BECF055BD54" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Tamaricaceae" genus="Tamarix" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Tamarix ramosissima" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="0" pageNumber="8176" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ramosissima">Tamarix ramosissima</taxonomicName>
is often treated as a synonym of 
<taxonomicName id="B46C1D887690E36A9BDA501F0116ED6D" authority="" authorityName="" class="Centricae" family="Chironomidae" genus="T." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="T. chinensis" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="8176" phylum="Diatomeae" rank="species" species="chinensis">T. chinensis</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="BBBFC458D21E0FC4512627E58B30C3B7" author="Welsh, S. L." journalOrPublisher="Print Services, Brigham Young University, Provo" pageId="0" pageNumber="8176" title="A Utah Flora" year="1993">Welsh et al. 1993</bibRefCitation>
), however genetic evidence supports their treatment as distinct species, albeit with extensive introgression and hybridization across its introduced range in the United States (
<bibRefCitation id="C59C4D57355E465F02EDCBAFC7D60F11" author="Gaskin, John F." journalOrPublisher="Biological Invasions" pageId="0" pageNumber="8176" pagination="1121 - 1130" title="Introgression between invasive saltcedars (Tamarixchinensis and Tamarixramosissima) in the USA" volume="11" year="2009">Gaskin and Kazmer 2009</bibRefCitation>
). Plants sampled previously from southeastern Utah have been identified as either back-crossed 
<taxonomicName id="98365F397F4D58603BA186FD4B9D240C" authority="" authorityName="" class="Centricae" family="Chironomidae" genus="T." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="T. ramosissima" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="8176" phylum="Diatomeae" rank="species" species="ramosissima">T. ramosissima</taxonomicName>
or F2 hybrids (
<bibRefCitation id="1A0886994A9939FB5D4E7040322D3703" author="Gaskin, John F." journalOrPublisher="Biological Invasions" pageId="0" pageNumber="8176" pagination="1121 - 1130" title="Introgression between invasive saltcedars (Tamarixchinensis and Tamarixramosissima) in the USA" volume="11" year="2009">Gaskin and Kazmer 2009</bibRefCitation>
); it seems extremely likely that our material would possess a similar genotype.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7E33EF085719D9DEFEA7A397EA2EF7A9" pageId="0" pageNumber="8176">
This species has previously been reported for the nearby San Rafael Swell (
<bibRefCitation id="4F5F58E63A273E7FC300604C495A346F" author="Harris, JG" journalOrPublisher="Great Basin Naturalist" pageId="0" pageNumber="8176" pagination="79 - 87" title="A vascular flora of the San Rafael Swell, Utah" volume="43" year="1983">Harris 1983</bibRefCitation>
). Only one population was encountered in the vicinity of MDRS, consisting of three shrubby trees and multiple seedlings, around Kent's Reservoir - a pond on the west side of Cow Dung Road north of MDRS (Fig. 47).
</paragraph>
